      "writtenOn": "2026-06-09T12:28:34Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Is there a way to structure code such a way that we can add support for Inventory items contained by chassis (M) and Control Interfaces (N) by just doing M + N implementation instead of M*N.",
      "revId": "83191888d3ab773176902eac389fa89fcdc30142",
      "serverId": "adbd0a64-1f21-4d83-b585-671fe73cb6e4"
    },
    {
      "unresolved": false,
      "key": {
        "uuid": "ce7ac715_7bd7eeed",
        "filename": "redfish-core/lib/control.hpp",
        "patchSetId": 14
      },
      "lineNbr": 411,
      "author": {
        "id": 1002790
      },
      "writtenOn": "2026-06-12T05:37:49Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "The root cause is that one Control resource\u0027s data is split across two interfaces: Control.OperatingClockSpeed (SetPoint/SettingMax/Min/ControlMode — uniform per control type, the N axis) and the controlled inventory item (AllowableMax/Min + PhysicalContext, currently read from Item.Accelerator\u0027s MaxSpeedInHz/MinSpeedInHz/Type — the M axis). \nThe only genuine M×N coupling is reading the allowable range from the inventory item, since each inventory type stores it under different properties. I think the cleanest fix is to expose the allowable range on Control.OperatingClockSpeed itself (add MaxSpeedInHz/MinSpeedInHz there); then bmcweb reads every control value from the control object (pure N) and the inventory item is only used to build the RelatedItem URI, which is a pure data table (pure M) — true M+N. I\u0027d propose doing that as a follow-up PDI + dbus-sensors change. WDYT?",
      "parentUuid": "72c56f6e_1c07321b",
      "revId": "83191888d3ab773176902eac389fa89fcdc30142",
      "serverId": "adbd0a64-1f21-4d83-b585-671fe73cb6e4"
    },
